In fact, they yelled at me for, you can't run the jet coming into the lab because it scares the shit out of everybody.

18:17.360 --> 18:19.160
How fast would the car go?

18:19.320 --> 18:19.720
212.

18:20.200 --> 18:20.600
Jesus.

18:21.060 --> 18:21.440
Yeah, yeah.

18:21.520 --> 18:23.040
On that car, it's super dangerous.

18:23.160 --> 18:24.560
I would never do that today.

18:24.560 --> 18:24.780
That's insane.

18:24.960 --> 18:25.780
Yeah, but...

18:25.780 --> 18:29.700
So you're putting, like, a Bugatti engine on a Honda Civic and you're like...

18:29.700 --> 18:31.360
Yeah, in a way, yeah.

18:32.820 --> 18:33.140
Unbelievable.

18:33.400 --> 18:34.040
Yeah, it's silly.

18:34.120 --> 18:36.320
But you're stupider when you're in your 20s, yeah.

18:36.500 --> 18:37.620
Well, what was your top speed?

18:38.580 --> 18:38.980
212.

18:39.200 --> 18:40.680
Yours was 212.

18:40.780 --> 18:40.980
Yeah.

18:41.140 --> 18:42.040
You went 212.

18:42.040 --> 18:43.840
El Mirage Dry Lake in California.

18:43.840 --> 18:44.680
You're insane.

18:45.920 --> 18:49.360
Maybe, but that's how fast the car went.

18:49.600 --> 18:55.420
But the Honda Civic is not set up for the jet engine that you put on it.

18:55.420 --> 18:58.140
Well, it was after I put it in there.

18:58.380 --> 19:01.840
Oh, so you helped with the suspension and some of that stuff.

19:02.040 --> 19:02.520
You improved.

19:02.700 --> 19:02.880
Wow.

19:03.000 --> 19:03.100
Yeah.

19:03.400 --> 19:04.400
That's impressive, man.

19:04.440 --> 19:05.020
That's cool.

19:06.940 --> 19:10.240
Well, while working at Los Alamos National Lab in 1982,

19:10.240 --> 19:14.160
the local newspaper did a front-page story on a jet car I had built.

19:15.040 --> 19:19.060
Coincidentally, Dr. Edward Teller was giving a speech at Los Alamos that same day.

19:22.500 --> 19:26.740
So Edward Teller, for the audience, was the creator of the hydrogen bomb.

19:27.780 --> 19:32.320
Coincidentally, that same day on the paper, if you turn over the front sheet,

19:32.620 --> 19:36.280
was the advertisement for Ed Teller coming the next day.

19:36.440 --> 19:36.840
Wow.

19:37.000 --> 19:38.980
Giving a lecture, you know, at the lab, so.

19:40.240 --> 19:45.460
So you go to, like, a talk he gives or something?

19:45.580 --> 19:47.000
Yeah, he was about to give a talk.

19:47.060 --> 19:47.820
I got there early.

19:48.020 --> 19:51.540
He's sitting outside reading the paper because the door was locked.

19:51.720 --> 19:51.940
Uh-huh.

19:51.940 --> 19:57.440
So that's, I wanted to go super early, too, because I thought maybe it's going to be crowded or whatever.

19:59.160 --> 20:05.560
He's reading the front page of the paper because, or else I really didn't know how to go out and say anything,

20:05.560 --> 20:07.540
but I went, oh, it's the perfect segue.

20:07.760 --> 20:09.660
He's already reading about me.

20:09.720 --> 20:12.720
So I was like, hi, Ed, I'm the guy you're reading about there.

20:12.720 --> 20:14.480
What was Edward Teller like?

20:14.860 --> 20:16.120
He's a grumpy old man.

20:17.380 --> 20:19.740
That's just the only way I could describe him.

20:19.940 --> 20:23.840
Did he have any sort of distinct accent or facial?

20:23.840 --> 20:24.700
Of course he has a distinct accent.

20:26.220 --> 20:27.480
Ed Teller, yeah.

20:27.580 --> 20:27.840
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

20:27.840 --> 20:28.700
A bit thick Hungarian.

20:28.700 --> 20:30.540
Yeah, he had giant eyebrows and, yeah.

20:30.720 --> 20:30.900
Yeah.

20:31.060 --> 20:33.120
I mean, he looked exactly like himself.

20:33.340 --> 20:34.040
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

20:34.700 --> 20:35.140
Fascinating.

20:35.300 --> 20:37.000
And so what was the conversation like?

20:37.040 --> 20:38.800
Are you like, hey, that, you know, that's me.

20:38.900 --> 20:40.360
And then what did he, what did he say?

20:40.860 --> 20:42.800
He said, well, that's, that's fascinating.

20:42.800 --> 20:46.140
But, you know, I can't remember it verbatim, but he said.

20:46.300 --> 20:48.080
But it is grossly impractical.

20:49.200 --> 20:54.620
I said, yeah, it's not made to be a practical, you know, mode of transportation.

20:55.120 --> 21:00.200
And then we only spoke for a short time and then you can hear the door unclick, swing open.

21:00.300 --> 21:02.160
And a guy greeted him, oh, Mr. Teller.

21:02.160 --> 21:05.760
And so they brought him in and, you know, that was that.

21:05.940 --> 21:13.980
But as time went on, I made reference to that meeting when I sent him a resume after I had moved on from Los Alamos.

21:14.320 --> 21:16.360
And he remembered me.

21:16.940 --> 21:22.780
And that's who directed me to EG&G, how this all started to go to S4.

21:22.780 --> 21:32.260
Have you ever seen, there's a, there's a video of, um, Edward Teller being questioned on his relationship with you?

21:32.500 --> 21:32.880
Yeah, yeah, of course.

21:32.880 --> 21:40.700
It's really funny because he, first of all, he goes into, he's being questioned on nuclear propulsion and he, like, doesn't want to get into it.

21:40.720 --> 21:41.420
It's very clear.

21:41.680 --> 21:44.520
And then he's questioning on you and he has the exact same reaction.

21:44.520 --> 21:47.840
It is, in my opinion, not interesting.

21:48.660 --> 21:50.520
I don't intend to answer it.

21:50.760 --> 21:53.960
If you ask me that question on camera, I will shut up.

21:54.200 --> 21:55.020
I will sit silent.

21:56.500 --> 21:58.840
You're not going to get an answer right on me on that.

21:59.900 --> 22:00.340
Okay.

22:02.260 --> 22:05.340
And if I ask you on camera if you know Bob Lazar, can you just say no?

22:06.920 --> 22:08.480
I will sit silently.

22:08.480 --> 22:16.760
I mean, I spoke to the guy before he went and interviewed Teller.

22:17.060 --> 22:18.760
He was one of Teller's students.

22:19.360 --> 22:23.320
And he said, you know, I'm going to bring up you to Teller.

22:23.420 --> 22:24.660
And I went, that would be awesome.

22:24.940 --> 22:25.140
Yeah.

22:25.280 --> 22:29.460
And it would be awesome to see how fast he denies me.

22:29.640 --> 22:29.860
Yeah.

22:30.020 --> 22:31.920
You know, and he did immediately.

22:32.280 --> 22:34.080
But he denied you in the same way.

22:34.080 --> 22:39.240
First, he goes, yeah, technically you could get, you know, a real power source from nuclear.

22:39.900 --> 22:43.420
And basically implying he knows a lot about it, but he's not going to talk about it.

22:43.480 --> 22:43.600
Yeah.

22:43.700 --> 22:47.240
I think he said, yeah, is there anything other than fish and refusion?

22:47.460 --> 22:47.880
That's right.

22:48.000 --> 22:50.320
No, nothing that anybody interested about.

22:50.460 --> 22:50.580
Yeah.

22:50.640 --> 22:53.200
But there's total annihilation, you know.

22:53.520 --> 22:59.000
And yeah, he just completely discounted that, which is interesting for Teller.

22:59.120 --> 23:04.060
Do you think that he is talking about, because you talk about this 115, you had a problem.

23:04.080 --> 23:05.560
I don't know if that's what he was referring to.

23:05.560 --> 23:08.760
Goes up to 116, and then you get this matter, antimatter annihilation thing.

23:08.760 --> 23:14.300
I don't know if that's what he was referring to, but he's also, but he's clearly not addressing

23:14.300 --> 23:17.000
the most powerful nuclear reaction there is.

23:17.060 --> 23:18.340
And why would he do that?

23:18.340 --> 23:24.300
And he's clearly also denying the nuclear knowledge in the same way that he's denying

23:24.300 --> 23:25.840
his link to you.

23:26.260 --> 23:29.060
Which to me is such a tell that he obviously met you.

23:29.700 --> 23:29.900
Yeah.

23:31.420 --> 23:33.340
It's really weird that he would do that.

23:33.340 --> 23:39.720
And so you were at Los Alamos, and were you working with other physicists at the time?

23:39.820 --> 23:39.900
Yeah, yeah.

23:39.900 --> 23:43.960
Or what was your main kind of like day-to-day responsibility there?

23:44.600 --> 23:46.440
Well, it changed.

23:46.440 --> 23:53.320
Um, I did some, I was building, I think, uh, this was for the particle accelerator.

23:53.500 --> 23:58.760
They wanted to be able to trim the voltage to a very fine degree.

23:59.040 --> 24:05.900
So I was building some high voltage power supplies, stuff that's insulated by fiber optics, so you

24:05.900 --> 24:12.940
can make adjustments, you know, from a distance without interfering with, you know, the electric

24:12.940 --> 24:13.940
fields or anything.

24:14.600 --> 24:20.120
Um, and day-to-day there was just maintenance on the targets and experiments we were doing.

24:20.320 --> 24:26.340
So it's cryogenics and, you know, dealing with, uh, high power magnets.

24:26.340 --> 24:29.060
And, I mean, what else?

24:29.180 --> 24:30.320
Radio actors' materials.

24:31.020 --> 24:31.080
Yeah.

24:31.520 --> 24:34.760
Um, you know, Los Alamos stuff.

24:34.900 --> 24:35.100
Yeah.

24:35.120 --> 24:39.320
I mean, I'm just trying to remember what I did every day, but it was, uh, nothing, it

24:39.320 --> 24:42.560
was, there was no really regular routine.

24:42.820 --> 24:43.080
Mm-hmm.

24:43.080 --> 24:48.920
You know, we'd either be working on getting ready to do an experiment, so we'd be working

24:48.920 --> 24:50.800
on, you know, the detection equipment.

24:51.000 --> 24:51.180
Yeah.

24:51.340 --> 24:52.880
Or setting up the experiment.

24:53.560 --> 25:03.260
And, um, it all had to do with, uh, you know, the output of the accelerator and adjusting

25:03.260 --> 25:03.620
that.

25:04.060 --> 25:05.840
So this was a particle accelerator?

25:06.100 --> 25:06.480
Yeah, yeah.

25:06.660 --> 25:07.340
Oh, interesting.

25:07.680 --> 25:11.200
Yeah, it's a half mile long linear accelerator in Los Alamos.

25:11.320 --> 25:11.720
Oh, cool.

25:11.720 --> 25:20.220
And the beam splits off, it, uh, it comes down and it, it splits off into different experimental

25:20.220 --> 25:20.800
areas.

25:21.000 --> 25:26.680
So you can conduct a whole bunch of different experiments, you know, just from one, one beam.

25:26.820 --> 25:30.420
And they can put different things in the targets to make different particles and go different

25:30.420 --> 25:30.920
directions.

25:30.920 --> 25:37.500
And depending on the speed of the particle going by and its spin and how long it's in transit,

25:37.500 --> 25:42.280
you can calculate its mass and, you know, backtrack and then put things together.

25:42.700 --> 25:48.740
And, you know, analogy I always gave was, uh, it's, it's like if you wanted to analyze

25:48.740 --> 25:52.280
a Swiss watch, but you really couldn't look inside.

25:52.280 --> 25:59.960
But so you could take it and throw it as hard as you can at a concrete wall and then it busts

25:59.960 --> 26:02.160
apart and all the pieces go flying off.

26:02.360 --> 26:02.520
Yeah.

26:03.040 --> 26:06.380
Well, by looking at those pieces, you could backtrack everything.

26:06.920 --> 26:06.980
Yeah.

26:07.020 --> 26:12.160
You could see if one was spinning a certain direction and you know, the rotation and how

26:12.160 --> 26:17.200
fast it came off, then, you know, the mass of it, if it was turning before and by the

26:17.200 --> 26:22.120
angles, you can put it back there and eventually you can reassemble the thing and see how it

26:22.120 --> 26:24.220
was made just from the particles flying apart.

26:24.400 --> 26:29.080
So essentially what an accelerator does is smash something apart and then we can figure

26:29.080 --> 26:32.760
out how it all goes together just by monitoring those particles.

26:33.020 --> 26:33.700
It's so cool.

26:34.360 --> 26:34.800
Yeah.

26:34.920 --> 26:37.820
So, I mean, that's, that's, that's what I did at Los Alamos.

26:37.820 --> 26:44.780
Did you, did you get the sense that there were two branches of science, science that

26:44.780 --> 26:47.880
was a little more classified and then public science?

26:48.100 --> 26:48.820
No, not at that point.

26:48.820 --> 26:49.540
Not at that point.

26:49.560 --> 26:50.120
Not at that point.

26:50.240 --> 26:51.780
I thought we were all on the same level.

26:52.080 --> 26:52.340
Yeah.

26:53.100 --> 27:00.840
Now I know, um, you can't say why they erased you from MIT and there are a lot of people out

27:00.840 --> 27:03.120
there who say you faked your educational credentials.

27:03.120 --> 27:09.040
You have very good, I think, reason that at least passes, you know, Joe Rogan and some

27:09.040 --> 27:11.480
other people who I really trust their sniff test.

27:12.160 --> 27:17.760
He said that he was working on something for the government at, and they sent him to MIT

27:17.760 --> 27:21.520
to learn something.

27:21.780 --> 27:27.380
But I will ask you, is there anything you can say high level that hints at why you can't

27:27.380 --> 27:29.500
talk about why you're at MIT?

27:29.500 --> 27:32.540
Well, I was sent there.

27:34.180 --> 27:34.780
Okay.

27:35.160 --> 27:44.960
And, um, if you're sent like there for a specific reason, um, maybe to do some classified research

27:44.960 --> 27:45.460
or work.

27:45.600 --> 27:45.820
Yep.

27:46.040 --> 27:48.840
Um, it's going to be off the books.

27:49.420 --> 27:50.020
Yeah.

27:50.020 --> 27:56.040
I mean, but it's also, you also can't talk about it because it's still, I mean, look,

27:56.120 --> 28:02.380
the government's never going to come and prosecute me for, at least I hope not, for releasing

28:02.380 --> 28:03.940
information about S4.

28:04.220 --> 28:04.480
Yep.

28:04.800 --> 28:12.380
But assuming I was working on a weapons system, that's always, it's still covered under the

28:12.380 --> 28:13.240
security agreement.

28:13.480 --> 28:16.940
And at this point in my life, I just don't want to make any waves.

28:16.940 --> 28:18.400
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

28:18.400 --> 28:19.300
So, um.

28:19.300 --> 28:20.340
No, I think that's very reasonable.

28:20.520 --> 28:27.300
It's also, I should note, and this is me talking and not you, MIT Long is a university, you know,

28:27.360 --> 28:28.400
affiliated research center.

28:28.480 --> 28:29.260
It's called the UARC.

28:29.620 --> 28:32.200
And they do all sorts of classified stuff.

28:32.300 --> 28:33.240
You know, they have a.

28:33.240 --> 28:33.580
Yeah, yeah.

28:33.660 --> 28:35.060
Super soldier program.

28:35.300 --> 28:37.640
They're, you know, we're always at the forefront of nanotechnology.

28:37.640 --> 28:40.760
And so, uh, the idea that, uh.

28:40.840 --> 28:46.720
Well, anything I would have potentially been working on wouldn't be so outlandish as super

28:46.720 --> 28:49.000
soldiers or it'd be just very conventional.

28:49.360 --> 28:49.640
Sure.

28:49.920 --> 28:50.340
Um.

28:50.940 --> 28:53.640
You know, but still classified material.

28:54.560 --> 28:54.900
Yeah.

28:54.960 --> 28:55.580
Touching stuff.

28:55.660 --> 29:00.760
I think, I think, I think it's just helpful because, um, this stuff is circulating out there.

29:00.760 --> 29:07.000
And, you know, the idea that you would get sent to that school specifically and work on

29:07.000 --> 29:09.720
something that you can't talk about is very feasible.

29:09.820 --> 29:11.420
I'm not saying that I did get sent, but if I would have gotten sent.

29:11.500 --> 29:11.940
Theoretically.

29:12.300 --> 29:12.700
Hypothetically.

29:12.800 --> 29:13.320
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

29:13.340 --> 29:14.260
You got sent there.

29:14.360 --> 29:19.060
If I got sent there, uh, you know, I, yeah, there's a very clear possibility I wouldn't be

29:19.060 --> 29:21.420
able to talk about it and I'd be working on some classified stuff.

29:22.700 --> 29:29.180
If you wanted to hire a guy who could think clearly out of the box and help solve problems,

29:29.180 --> 29:34.020
but who could be discredited if you needed to do that, Bob was probably the best person

29:34.020 --> 29:35.240
in the country at the time.

29:35.520 --> 29:36.600
He was perfect for it.

29:40.060 --> 29:45.660
George Knapp was originally this very instrumental part of Breaking Your Story in 1989 as part

29:45.660 --> 29:46.340
of KLAS.

29:47.560 --> 29:51.360
Uh, did you, you took him to Los Alamos, is that right, at some point?

29:51.360 --> 29:58.140
Yeah, I told him all this Los Alamos stuff and, um, I said, well, let's go there.

29:58.220 --> 29:59.060
I'll show you.

29:59.180 --> 30:02.820
And, uh, security was a little more lax back then.

30:03.660 --> 30:10.440
Uh, so I, we got in a plane and, uh, you just rented a car and, you know, at that time,

30:10.800 --> 30:12.560
everyone I knew still worked there.

30:13.020 --> 30:16.640
So including the guards, we're getting in, hey, Bill, Bob, you're back, you know?

30:16.640 --> 30:21.720
And so we're in and, uh, you know, just took charge everywhere.

30:21.880 --> 30:25.360
There's my desk, here's this, and, you know, walk in here.

30:25.360 --> 30:27.820
And I still knew combinations to places of water.

30:28.100 --> 30:32.700
I'm sure it was not all a hundred percent legal, but yeah, George just walked around,

30:32.840 --> 30:35.400
filmed everything, spoke to people that I worked with.

30:35.400 --> 30:38.940
And he said, all right, we can check that box off.

30:38.940 --> 30:41.180
And then, um, we went back.

30:41.340 --> 30:41.600
Yeah.

30:42.040 --> 30:49.680
And so, cause I also, you know, again, I want to, uh, uh, address some of these like detracting

30:49.680 --> 30:51.760
comments circulating online.

30:51.760 --> 30:56.480
And there are people who are like, oh, he just quizzed the physicists, you know, at Los

30:56.480 --> 30:59.240
Alamos, but he really had some other job there or something.

30:59.820 --> 31:05.000
First of all, like your, your, uh, description of a particle accelerator and, and how to actually,

31:05.000 --> 31:08.360
you know, detect subatomic particles, I think was, you know, first class.

31:08.600 --> 31:13.480
And then second, you have a guy in George Knapp, which you are, you have to either, um,

31:13.900 --> 31:19.740
accuse him of some sort of collusion or something in his orientation towards you or admit that

31:19.740 --> 31:23.600
you showed him around, people knew your name, you know, he saw it.

31:23.740 --> 31:23.900
Yeah.

31:23.900 --> 31:24.120
Yeah.

31:24.120 --> 31:28.320
And clearly he was trying to suss you out by asking you to invite him.

31:28.420 --> 31:28.780
Right.

31:29.120 --> 31:29.520
Presumably.

31:29.520 --> 31:29.740
Yeah.

31:30.140 --> 31:30.580
Yeah.

31:30.660 --> 31:34.080
I just don't pay attention to the detractors and the nonsense.

31:34.440 --> 31:39.900
I mean, to me, we're, we're, we're past that.

31:41.180 --> 31:42.540
Now I never met Dr.

31:42.620 --> 31:47.660
Teller again, but in 1988, when I decided to reenter the scientific community, I sent him

31:47.660 --> 31:49.820
him a resume and inquired about a job.

31:50.500 --> 31:50.900
Dr.

31:50.980 --> 31:54.940
Teller responded by telephone and told me that he was no longer active, but just functioned

31:54.940 --> 31:56.440
in a chief consultant capacity.

31:56.960 --> 31:59.780
He gave me the name of a contact to call in Las Vegas.

32:00.180 --> 32:04.040
I made that call and things progressed from there until I got into the program at S4.

32:04.400 --> 32:07.160
And so you sent him the resume and he remembers you somehow.

32:07.880 --> 32:08.200
And which.

32:08.340 --> 32:08.500
Yeah.

32:08.520 --> 32:10.780
Cause I made mention of the jet car in Los Alamos.

32:11.720 --> 32:15.660
And then, and then he sends your resume to EG&G and then you get a job there.

32:15.660 --> 32:17.460
I don't, I don't know if he sent it.

32:17.680 --> 32:25.740
He, uh, when he did reply to me, he, he gave me information, contact information for EG&G.

32:26.340 --> 32:31.040
So I don't know if he said, or just have a look at this young man or something like that.

32:31.040 --> 32:35.580
Or, or if he did send the resumes, I don't know what happened behind the scenes.

32:35.720 --> 32:38.000
Did you know anything about EG&G at the time or.

32:38.180 --> 32:39.940
I know they did measurements.

32:39.940 --> 32:44.540
They did all the, uh, I mean, those are the guys that came out and figured how to, you

32:44.540 --> 32:50.900
know, photograph, uh, you know, an exploding nuclear bomb without it getting overexposed.

32:51.320 --> 32:57.540
Um, they did all kinds of things, make giant flash tubes so you can photograph cities from

32:57.540 --> 32:59.220
bombers and, and stuff.

32:59.380 --> 33:03.780
So, um, that's about all I knew.

33:03.860 --> 33:08.780
I knew they were just, uh, you know, a contractor that did weird stuff for the government, but,

33:08.780 --> 33:11.820
you know, leaning heavily in the nuclear testing area.

33:11.820 --> 33:18.160
It's a company that is the namesake of Doc Edgerton, who was MIT faculty actually, and.

33:18.540 --> 33:20.360
Edgerton, Grimmerhausen, and Greer.

33:20.440 --> 33:21.200
There you go.

33:21.920 --> 33:24.060
Many types of cameras will be in use.

33:24.540 --> 33:30.760
The most important are fast packs, which operate up to 9,000 frames per second and expose their

33:30.760 --> 33:33.140
entire footage in a fraction of a second.

33:33.140 --> 33:38.460
Have you looked at any of the other, you know, I obviously are really into nuclear and then

33:38.460 --> 33:39.860
you worked on UFOs.

33:39.960 --> 33:43.860
There's this amazing book that I always cite that I'm sure you're aware of Luigi called

33:43.860 --> 33:46.980
UFOs and Nukes by a friend of mine named Robert Hastings.

33:47.380 --> 33:54.500
And he talks about UFOs like Tic Tacs, saucers, orbs, all these different shapes and sizes of

33:54.500 --> 33:57.700
UFOs showing up at nuclear bases all across the U.S.

33:57.700 --> 33:58.860
I've certainly heard that.

33:59.080 --> 33:59.820
Isn't that interesting?

34:00.000 --> 34:05.600
And there are 167 whistleblowers who are on what's called the PRP program, where they

34:05.600 --> 34:08.960
have to report if they're taking ibuprofen because they're guarding the crown jewels of

34:08.960 --> 34:09.660
American defense.

34:09.880 --> 34:10.320
Oh, really?

34:10.960 --> 34:12.040
167 of these guys.

34:12.200 --> 34:12.560
Wow.

34:12.840 --> 34:13.080
Yeah.

34:13.180 --> 34:15.400
There's really 167 of those guys?

34:16.680 --> 34:17.940
167 of these guys.

34:18.300 --> 34:18.860
It's really wild.

34:18.980 --> 34:19.680
And they have teeth.

34:20.200 --> 34:20.340
Yeah.

34:20.480 --> 34:21.480
That's incredible.

34:21.480 --> 34:24.380
I mean, that should be investigated further.

34:24.640 --> 34:27.220
And I'm sure it is, but not publicly.

34:27.840 --> 34:30.280
But I mean, you're talking about nuclear sites.

34:30.460 --> 34:36.220
If you're talking about nuclear sites, you are at the very core of national security.

34:36.440 --> 34:43.440
So my point is, is if you're doing the photography of that early on, you've got to have some asymmetric

34:43.440 --> 34:44.960
knowledge of UFO stuff.

34:45.040 --> 34:45.920
That would be my guess.

34:46.260 --> 34:46.440
Yeah.

34:46.480 --> 34:50.560
They were the guys documenting and photographing everything from every angle from everywhere.

34:50.560 --> 34:51.000
Yes.

34:51.300 --> 34:55.980
So if, in fact, all that stuff was going on, EG&G had to catch something.

34:56.360 --> 34:56.700
Totally.

34:57.400 --> 35:03.520
And EG&G, it keeps coming up for me, too, in my own investigations.

35:04.100 --> 35:09.580
Even there's this thing called the Wilson Davis memo where the scientist who actually lives

35:09.580 --> 35:17.020
in Austin, his name is Eric Davis, meets with the head of J-2 Joint Chiefs, under whose purview

35:17.020 --> 35:18.760
is all military technology.

35:18.760 --> 35:20.360
A guy named Admiral Thomas Wilson.

35:20.900 --> 35:23.180
And they're in the parking lot of EG&G.

35:23.360 --> 35:29.160
And Thomas Wilson is like furious that he doesn't have oversight over this specific corporate

35:29.160 --> 35:33.060
program, which seems to be reverse engineering exotic UFO material.

35:33.400 --> 35:36.360
So you get a job at EG&G.

35:37.360 --> 35:39.340
What's your first touch point there?

35:39.340 --> 35:42.340
And so you have a little bit of context, but...

35:42.340 --> 35:44.340
Yeah, I originally went in there.

35:44.820 --> 35:46.640
I didn't know what the job was.

35:46.680 --> 35:46.920
Yeah.

35:46.920 --> 35:49.060
But they interviewed me for that.

35:49.320 --> 35:53.780
And somewhere in the middle of it, they said, you know, we actually have a different job

35:53.780 --> 35:56.040
that we're thinking of plugging you into now.

35:56.200 --> 36:00.680
I think I went to the bathroom and when I came back, they said, we're changing channels.

36:01.320 --> 36:02.340
We think we have.

36:02.340 --> 36:11.360
And I think, so I don't know if they were both something at S-4 or something else was

36:11.360 --> 36:15.220
going to be for EG&G or the Department of Naval Intelligence.

36:15.540 --> 36:19.800
And then they thought maybe S-4 would be a, you know, a better fit.

36:20.120 --> 36:24.680
I don't know what, again, what went on behind the scenes, but there were two jobs there and

36:24.680 --> 36:26.940
they decided I'd be better off with the second one.

36:27.020 --> 36:31.940
And the second one was S-4 out at the Papoose Lake area.

36:32.360 --> 36:34.340
And what were they screening for?

36:34.480 --> 36:38.700
Like, what do you think they were asking you and trying to get at?

36:38.780 --> 36:41.680
And then when you go to the bathroom, why do they shift?

36:41.680 --> 36:42.080
I don't know.

36:42.520 --> 36:47.260
And they say, this guy is actually going to, that UFO thing we're stuck on, this guy is

36:47.260 --> 36:48.460
going to break it wide open.

36:48.580 --> 36:50.500
He could be a good hire there.

36:50.500 --> 36:51.260
Do you have any sense?

36:51.260 --> 36:51.880
I don't think that's what they said.

36:51.880 --> 37:00.920
But I think they were stuck and I think they kept, you know, just because of the way the

37:00.920 --> 37:07.300
place is arranged, they kept trying to attack the problem from the same direction all the

37:07.300 --> 37:11.320
time, you know, which is only going to yield the same result.

37:11.440 --> 37:15.420
In fact, if you expect anything else, you're nuts.

37:16.380 --> 37:18.260
That's the definition of crazy, right?

37:18.320 --> 37:20.460
Doing the same thing and expecting different results.

37:21.880 --> 37:31.660
But, um, yeah, most of their questions was not about, um, my technical knowledge or work

37:31.660 --> 37:32.380
experience.

37:32.520 --> 37:39.360
It was what I did after work and, you know, like the projects I built, why did you do

37:39.360 --> 37:39.760
that?

37:40.280 --> 37:47.120
Um, and I think they were just looking at trying to find somebody that was outside of the box.

37:47.120 --> 37:50.040
And I think that's where I fit.

37:50.100 --> 37:55.320
Cause before that you had really straight laced scientists, physicists, technicians, you

37:55.320 --> 37:57.460
know, that abided by the rules and all that.

37:57.540 --> 38:00.680
And they look, we need a little push from another direction.

38:01.160 --> 38:02.840
And I mean, it's my guess.

38:02.900 --> 38:04.600
I think that's why they popped me in there.

38:04.760 --> 38:06.880
At that point, do you have any idea what you're getting yourself into?

38:07.100 --> 38:08.200
No, no.

38:08.320 --> 38:12.560
But the, you know, they said it's at a remote area and the work hours can vary.

38:12.560 --> 38:17.200
Some people are out there for, uh, two weeks on one week off.

38:17.400 --> 38:17.500
Yeah.

38:17.780 --> 38:22.840
Um, some people, and you know, it depends if they're married or not or anything and, you

38:22.840 --> 38:24.640
know, can spend that much time out there.

38:24.940 --> 38:30.080
Some people only go out three days a week and, you know, so, and some people are just

38:30.080 --> 38:35.220
on call and, you know, for the time being, it would probably just probably need you sporadically

38:35.220 --> 38:38.820
going out there on call and, you know, until we get you up to speed.

38:38.820 --> 38:40.680
And do you have any problem with traveling?

38:40.940 --> 38:41.720
I said, no, no, no.

38:41.900 --> 38:42.080
You know?

38:42.160 --> 38:47.300
So I thought, wow, if it's out in the desert, um, it's probably, I thought it was the only

38:47.300 --> 38:50.740
thing I knew about the desert was at that time, it's a nuclear test site.

38:51.020 --> 38:56.880
So I thought, I thought it was weapons related and, you know, specifically nuclear weapon related.

38:57.660 --> 39:03.280
And I was going to be at, uh, you know, the nuclear test site at somewhere, you know,

39:03.280 --> 39:04.400
stationed near Mercury.

39:08.820 --> 39:15.500
The way it worked was they'd call me at random days and they'd say, Mr. Lazard is now such

39:15.500 --> 39:16.180
and such time.

39:16.480 --> 39:17.940
We need you to come out today.

39:18.280 --> 39:19.220
So I'd go out there.

39:19.480 --> 39:24.760
I'd drive out to EG&G Special Projects, which was right in McCarran Airport at that time.

39:24.940 --> 39:30.260
I'd go through a little security there and then out on the tarmac and board one of the

39:30.260 --> 39:30.960
Janet flights.

39:31.220 --> 39:34.980
They were only used by the government for going back and forth to the test site.

39:34.980 --> 39:44.460
Yeah, we just took off and landed.

39:44.880 --> 39:44.960
Yeah.

39:44.980 --> 39:50.820
And, uh, I still thought I was at the, you know, I didn't know what I was at, Area 51.

39:51.320 --> 39:51.580
Yep.

39:52.400 --> 39:55.320
And you land at Area 51.

39:55.520 --> 39:55.740
Yeah.

39:55.820 --> 39:58.840
And first of all, at that time, Area 51 meant nothing.

39:58.840 --> 40:01.240
So it's just, this is known as Area 51.

40:01.640 --> 40:01.940
Okay.

40:02.380 --> 40:05.800
As all the, all the, you know, the test sites split up into areas.

40:05.960 --> 40:07.340
It's Area 2, Area 5.

40:07.480 --> 40:08.380
So it's 51.

40:09.040 --> 40:09.440
Okay.

40:09.820 --> 40:12.560
At what point, uh, do you go to ask for?

40:12.920 --> 40:17.500
You know, these, I've told the story so much and it's been so long.

40:17.580 --> 40:21.140
All the days kind of mix and infuse into one now.

40:21.140 --> 40:24.020
So I can't separate what you did on that day.

40:24.100 --> 40:25.280
What'd you do on the third day?

40:25.500 --> 40:26.440
I don't know.

40:26.700 --> 40:32.080
You know, it's just, um, of course, but I don't think we drove down on the first day.

40:32.300 --> 40:34.680
I think it was just a paperwork and stuff day.

40:34.840 --> 40:40.320
Uh, but the second day for sure, we drove down, um, got in the bus and it was a long bumpy

40:40.320 --> 40:40.800
ride.

40:41.300 --> 40:47.660
Um, and that the windows were blacked out on the bus and it was just a navy blue painted

40:47.660 --> 40:52.740
bus and it, it seemed like we went South, um, by the time we got there, it got off the

40:52.740 --> 40:53.140
bus.

40:53.300 --> 40:56.680
I, I mean, the sun was setting to my right.

40:57.080 --> 40:58.680
And then what happens next?

40:59.440 --> 41:02.000
Well, I mean, when you mean when I got there?

41:02.020 --> 41:02.320
Yeah.

41:02.440 --> 41:02.640
Yeah.

41:02.760 --> 41:09.420
I mean, that's where we, Dennis led me in, um, and he's Dennis for the audience.

41:09.900 --> 41:15.780
I guess you can call him my supervisor, but he was kind of my shadow and everything.

41:15.780 --> 41:17.240
He was just attached to me.

41:17.240 --> 41:18.680
This is Dennis Mariani.

41:18.820 --> 41:19.400
Dennis Mariani.

41:19.740 --> 41:20.000
Yeah.

41:20.480 --> 41:21.960
And so he leads you in.

41:22.220 --> 41:22.560
Yeah.

41:22.580 --> 41:23.440
He leads me in.

41:23.540 --> 41:25.080
There's a, there's a guard there.

41:25.580 --> 41:33.420
Um, we get past him and then they had to train the, uh, hand reader to give me a, a card

41:33.420 --> 41:34.800
to open the doors.

41:34.940 --> 41:38.720
So that's the first time I saw that hand scanner.

41:39.100 --> 41:40.180
I get the card.

41:40.240 --> 41:44.560
He shows me this, you swipe on the door and it records every time you come in and out

41:44.560 --> 41:45.640
and do everything.

41:45.640 --> 41:48.500
And is there a bodyguard or like, uh, no, no.

41:48.560 --> 41:50.260
Once you're in the room with the scanner, there's nothing.

41:50.380 --> 41:56.680
There's just a door you open up, but it's just a really long, really long corridor and

41:56.680 --> 41:59.240
just kind of, it's not modern looks old.

41:59.240 --> 42:02.520
It's just painted cinder block with light green and dark green.

42:03.100 --> 42:05.380
Kind of looked at my old kindergarten or something.

42:05.840 --> 42:07.320
It's this vast expanse.

42:07.400 --> 42:10.820
And is all of it underground or in a mountain or?

42:10.900 --> 42:12.760
It's kind of on the side of a mountain.

42:12.840 --> 42:13.040
Okay.

42:13.520 --> 42:17.500
You know, it's, so the hangers are right on the side or it's a hill.

42:17.580 --> 42:19.780
I guess whatever you want to describe it.

42:19.780 --> 42:20.040
Sure.

42:20.040 --> 42:23.960
So the hangers are there and then the corridor is in back of the hangers.

42:24.100 --> 42:25.940
So that gives you hangar access.

42:26.160 --> 42:27.520
And there were nine hangers.

42:27.700 --> 42:30.720
So, um, and they're fairly big.

42:30.720 --> 42:33.900
So that explains why the corridors were so long.

42:33.900 --> 42:39.500
And so you're in there, you see this vast expanse, then what happens?

42:40.060 --> 42:43.620
We went to review the briefings first.

42:43.840 --> 42:45.620
So that was off to the right.

42:45.840 --> 42:53.600
We came in, there was a desk there had, somebody had already laid out all the, uh, the briefings,

42:53.660 --> 42:56.140
which were summaries of the projects going on.

42:56.540 --> 43:03.160
So they didn't go in depth, but in case your project connected to some of these in some way,

43:03.160 --> 43:07.120
you had to have a brief overview of what else was going on.

43:07.380 --> 43:11.580
Project Galileo was the first, uh, you know, the first briefing on there.

43:12.300 --> 43:13.560
And that was your project.

43:13.660 --> 43:13.800
Yeah.

43:13.900 --> 43:15.960
And then, but you had other briefings as well.

43:16.200 --> 43:16.500
Yeah.

43:16.580 --> 43:16.760
Yeah.

43:16.900 --> 43:19.500
And, and, and that was project looking glass.

43:19.740 --> 43:21.540
Looking glass and, uh, sidekick.

43:21.680 --> 43:22.600
And sidekick.

43:22.720 --> 43:23.000
Okay.

43:23.060 --> 43:23.240
Yeah.

43:23.280 --> 43:28.440
And so I imagine you take most interest in Galileo and, but you also look through looking

43:28.440 --> 43:29.360
glass and sidekick.

43:29.360 --> 43:29.960
Is that right?

43:29.960 --> 43:39.900
But Galileo dealt with the propulsion system of the craft and, um, and the directives that

43:39.900 --> 43:46.760
are given, uh, there were two primary directives is one to, uh, duplicate the propulsion system

43:46.760 --> 43:51.980
or components thereof with available materials, available earth materials.

43:51.980 --> 44:00.260
It's, uh, um, and directive two was to be able to remotely, um, disable the operation of the

44:00.260 --> 44:00.660
system.

44:01.280 --> 44:05.060
Uh, and some, I don't know how it was worded somewhere.

44:05.240 --> 44:07.800
The word at all costs was in there.

44:07.920 --> 44:14.920
So, um, that was really a high priority, but they wanted to, uh, they certainly wanted to

44:14.920 --> 44:18.120
duplicate it, but they really wanted to disable it.

44:18.120 --> 44:22.840
I do think that's an important distinction in the mandate of the program.

44:23.080 --> 44:30.300
It's to not necessarily reverse engineer, but to parallel engineer, find ways to, with

44:30.300 --> 44:35.440
terrestrial normal prosaic engineering, build.

44:35.560 --> 44:35.740
Yeah.

44:35.740 --> 44:37.900
Or come up with a hybrid system, something.

44:38.200 --> 44:38.380
Yeah.

44:38.520 --> 44:43.700
I mean, the, the bottom line is we want to produce the effects this machine is having.

44:43.700 --> 44:50.400
So just do it in any, yeah, however, however you can just, yeah, just do it.

44:50.520 --> 44:56.720
Which makes sense given the skillset they seem to take interest in with you because you are

44:56.720 --> 44:58.820
this outside of the box thinker.

44:58.820 --> 44:59.060
Yeah.

44:59.360 --> 45:05.800
You're not this prim and proper traditional academic or something who does not want to

45:05.800 --> 45:12.620
break rules who might be extremely high IQ, but, uh, isn't necessarily rebellious in the

45:12.620 --> 45:16.220
way they think, they think within these sort of narrow confines they're given.

45:16.580 --> 45:16.660
Yeah.

45:16.740 --> 45:21.340
They were, they were just looking to come at another angle and maybe we can, you know,

45:21.400 --> 45:22.240
uncover something.

45:22.440 --> 45:27.200
And, and just for the audience, what is sidekick and what is project looking glass?

45:27.520 --> 45:29.960
Sidekick was the weapon potential of the craft.

45:30.240 --> 45:36.620
The craft, if you're familiar with it, has three of the, uh, emitters on the bottom look

45:36.620 --> 45:43.900
like large trash cans and they send out the gravity waves or whatever form of energy is,

45:44.020 --> 45:53.360
but excuse me, sidekick dealt with using those to focus a particle beam to stop it from diverging.

45:53.740 --> 45:59.480
So there was, it, it appeared to be there, there was some sort of weapon potential of doing

45:59.480 --> 45:59.840
that.

46:00.260 --> 46:01.940
Like a directed energy weapon.

46:01.940 --> 46:04.120
Yeah, I think it was a particle weapon.

46:04.340 --> 46:11.340
So, um, I don't know where the, what the source was, but that's, that's just what the briefing

46:11.340 --> 46:12.200
contained in it.

46:12.780 --> 46:13.500
And, um.

46:13.900 --> 46:17.420
Are you given any other context before reading these documents?

46:17.700 --> 46:17.960
No.

46:18.420 --> 46:21.540
And when you're reading these documents, what, what's going through your.

46:21.660 --> 46:25.560
No, I mean, some of the stuff in there was just nonsense.

46:25.560 --> 46:29.640
I mean, and you wonder, is this like a test?

46:30.120 --> 46:38.320
Um, you know, there is stuff like, you know, the aliens had made 65 corrections to, um, you

46:38.320 --> 46:40.740
know, in the evolution of humans and things.

46:40.740 --> 46:47.380
And as Barry explained to me, um, he said, look, they keep everything classified here,

46:47.380 --> 46:54.000
but if somebody says something, you know, and they hear it on the grapevine, they said,

46:54.080 --> 46:59.400
yeah, they've got a disc, an alien craft at, you know, down at the test site.

46:59.520 --> 47:03.780
They don't know where it comes from, but everybody that they give briefings or information to,

47:03.860 --> 47:07.160
they put unique nonsense information there.

47:07.160 --> 47:13.080
So like if I had said anything, they, you know, I said, yeah, there's flying saucers

47:13.080 --> 47:15.500
down there and aliens made 65 corrections.

47:15.700 --> 47:20.540
They go, Lazar is the guy that, that, so that's, I think they put it in there to attach

47:20.540 --> 47:26.200
to a person, you know, he got this and they make it something enticing to say.

47:26.720 --> 47:28.860
So you go through these briefings, what happens next?

47:29.300 --> 47:35.900
At some point I went to the nurse who, um, it was the only female that was there.

47:35.900 --> 47:43.180
Uh, she, she said, you know, we have to do an allergen test and I guess they had a bunch

47:43.180 --> 47:45.240
of samples from different materials.

47:45.380 --> 47:50.960
They do a little grid on my arm and then just pricked them and, you know, waited for a reaction.

47:51.960 --> 47:57.960
Um, they gave me something to drink, which is supposedly supposed to boost my immune system.

47:57.960 --> 48:00.600
It was a, you know, a deep orange, yellow color.

48:00.780 --> 48:05.320
And I think that was because the vitamin B was in there and I can, I can taste that

48:05.320 --> 48:07.540
because it's really a nasty taste.

48:07.740 --> 48:08.580
What did it taste like?

48:08.800 --> 48:08.980
Yeah.

48:09.040 --> 48:11.100
Like a vitamin B solution.

48:11.240 --> 48:11.460
Okay.

48:11.560 --> 48:14.220
But it did, but it also had a pine taste to it.

48:14.480 --> 48:16.640
But anyway, that was that.

48:16.720 --> 48:18.820
I wasn't allergic to anything as it turned out.

48:18.820 --> 48:25.400
And eventually get it, go in and was introduced to Barry, who's going to be my lab partner.

48:25.720 --> 48:31.980
And, um, you know, from what I understand, I was replacing somebody that he worked with.

48:32.340 --> 48:32.440
Hmm.

48:33.040 --> 48:34.360
What was Barry like?

48:35.100 --> 48:35.920
Barry, I don't know.

48:35.940 --> 48:37.220
How would you describe Barry?

48:37.620 --> 48:39.600
Barry was very enthusiastic.

48:40.020 --> 48:40.220
Yeah.

48:40.220 --> 48:46.280
He was, he was really happy I was there and, uh, really excited to show me stuff.

48:46.580 --> 48:50.100
Um, but clearly a lot had been done before I got there.

48:50.280 --> 48:50.420
Yeah.

48:50.940 --> 48:55.140
If this was new, everything would be white, right?

48:55.280 --> 49:00.720
Everybody would be in, you know, I mean, you always want labs and everything white in case

49:00.720 --> 49:04.220
you see a little speck of dust or a part falls somewhere you can identify them.

49:04.340 --> 49:09.640
You wouldn't have, you know, wooden lamp or lab benches and things like that.

49:09.640 --> 49:15.220
You'd probably have people in full respirator suits if they're just beginning, but these

49:15.220 --> 49:22.240
guys had reached a point where it was nonchalant, where they were, they were touching, you know,

49:22.300 --> 49:23.400
working with this stuff.

49:23.580 --> 49:29.140
And, um, you know, it really wasn't a thing as if they were taking apart a car engine.

49:29.420 --> 49:34.520
So, um, they had made a lot of progress and they weren't afraid of what they were working

49:34.520 --> 49:34.840
with.

49:34.920 --> 49:38.020
Although we were plenty afraid of the reactor.

49:38.020 --> 49:43.540
And, and you, at no point were you like, this could be some like, you know, anti-gravity

49:43.540 --> 49:46.900
secret program that, you know, I just wasn't cleared to.

49:47.360 --> 49:47.480
No.

49:47.920 --> 49:48.160
Okay.

49:48.800 --> 49:53.080
I mean, initially when I first saw it, I went, oh, that's what this whole thing's about.

49:53.200 --> 49:58.380
You know, it's, it's just, it's just our new fighter and it looks like a flying saucer.

49:58.480 --> 50:00.960
So that's why people believe in flying saucers.

50:00.960 --> 50:07.640
Cause they see these new fighters flying around and, you know, but, um, yeah, it became quickly

50:07.640 --> 50:09.300
obvious that that wasn't the case.

50:09.300 --> 50:11.380
Like we have no idea how the thing works.

50:11.520 --> 50:18.160
It does stuff that's physically impossible and there's no country in the world could make

50:18.160 --> 50:22.480
something like that or have the power density that it has.

50:22.480 --> 50:24.620
It's an inconceivable.

50:25.060 --> 50:30.640
So to, you know, to, to affect space and time, look, if another country was able to build

50:30.640 --> 50:38.160
something like that, the United States wouldn't exist, you know, to anybody who, who's a detractor,

50:38.340 --> 50:45.180
who doesn't, who could think maybe this was a U S object, something man-made or something

50:45.180 --> 50:46.580
that they put there as a prop.

50:46.580 --> 50:52.120
Some people would say, do you think they were trying to deceive Lazar or other people and

50:52.120 --> 50:58.480
all that there's, because I built it, there's one physical aspect of it that is impossible

50:58.480 --> 50:59.920
to build period.

50:59.920 --> 51:06.320
A hundred percent not possible is it's as far as if we have to consider it being a 50 to

51:06.320 --> 51:14.120
almost 53 foot diameter craft, the main level, which is the level that Bob was able to access

51:14.120 --> 51:22.020
and, and, and at one point stand up in the middle of that main level is in the center

51:22.020 --> 51:22.820
of the disc.

51:23.600 --> 51:30.800
And there is nothing that was visually witnessed on the bottom level when he peaked, that is

51:30.800 --> 51:36.460
a supporting column holding that 53 foot diameter floor.

51:37.000 --> 51:40.360
We have nothing on earth.

51:40.460 --> 51:40.620
Yeah.

51:40.620 --> 51:42.120
There is no material.

51:42.120 --> 51:45.840
You know, that's, that's the first I've ever heard of that angle.

51:45.940 --> 51:47.460
That's, that's really interesting.

51:47.620 --> 51:47.960
That's right.

51:47.980 --> 51:48.740
Well, it's because I built it.

51:48.880 --> 51:49.020
Yeah.

51:49.320 --> 51:52.720
I think you know more about the craft at this point.

51:52.720 --> 51:59.520
Because of the thickness of the floor that we could see because of the lip of the access

51:59.520 --> 52:02.480
way, we could see the thickness of the floor.

52:02.480 --> 52:07.140
Also where the honeycomb hatchway is, you could see the thickness of the floor.

52:07.860 --> 52:08.240
That thickness.

52:08.240 --> 52:08.360
Yeah.

52:08.360 --> 52:09.980
52 feet diameter.

52:10.260 --> 52:11.700
There is nothing on earth.

52:11.700 --> 52:12.500
With no central support.

52:12.540 --> 52:17.880
That would not be doing boring like this and maybe, and potentially collapse.

52:18.080 --> 52:19.140
There's nothing.

52:19.280 --> 52:20.300
We have nothing.

52:20.440 --> 52:22.380
That's, that's a completely unique.

52:22.540 --> 52:22.800
Yeah.

52:22.920 --> 52:24.180
Structural anomaly.

52:24.300 --> 52:24.480
Yeah.

52:24.480 --> 52:27.700
Good job, Luigi.

52:27.900 --> 52:28.160
Yeah.

52:28.960 --> 52:29.440
Yeah.

52:29.580 --> 52:33.220
No, I never, never even entertained that.

52:33.300 --> 52:34.200
That's fascinating.

52:34.400 --> 52:34.640
Yeah.

52:34.660 --> 52:35.940
That's, that's great.

52:36.080 --> 52:38.300
But that's, that's a hundred percent true.

52:38.400 --> 52:38.540
Yeah.

52:38.780 --> 52:38.940
Yeah.

52:38.940 --> 52:40.380
There's nothing that can do that.

52:40.560 --> 52:40.780
Yeah.

52:41.080 --> 52:42.000
That's so interesting.

52:42.760 --> 52:45.240
What is the color of the craft itself?

52:45.240 --> 52:54.760
It's kind of a pewter, stainless looking, but it's, Luigi and I were talking about this

52:54.760 --> 52:55.480
the other day.

52:56.520 --> 53:01.660
It, it looks different close up than it does far away.

53:03.520 --> 53:04.040
Describe.

53:04.200 --> 53:04.780
How so?

53:05.420 --> 53:06.920
Jeez, I wish I could.

53:06.980 --> 53:08.780
I've tried to describe this a lot.

53:08.780 --> 53:16.140
And, uh, what's interesting is that I, my friend, Gene Huff, who was my kind of confidant

53:16.140 --> 53:16.900
at the time.

53:17.020 --> 53:21.600
And, um, you know, I tell him about this stuff and I said, you know, one of the weirdest

53:21.600 --> 53:27.140
things is if you're, if you're close to it, you know, it, it, it looks like the craft

53:27.140 --> 53:31.040
and it, and when you get far away, it doesn't look right.

53:31.940 --> 53:33.560
It looks more like a cartoon.

53:33.560 --> 53:42.020
Um, and, um, so Luigi spending two and a half or three years modeling this and getting it

53:42.020 --> 53:48.960
in and sure as hell, whatever they did, uh, Luigi will probably best tell you about that.

53:49.380 --> 53:53.820
Um, when they take the camera and they put it in the hanger and look at it close up, it

53:53.820 --> 53:54.600
looks like it should.

53:54.720 --> 53:57.500
And if they back it off, it doesn't look the same.

53:57.600 --> 54:03.060
It looks, so they were able to, whether intentionally or accidentally kind of duplicate it.

54:03.060 --> 54:09.080
I mean, they've got the model so close that it has, it's taken on some of the characteristics

54:09.080 --> 54:10.620
of the actual craft.

54:11.820 --> 54:15.660
And there's a part of the craft that you describe as blacker than black.

54:15.800 --> 54:16.640
Is that right?

54:17.180 --> 54:17.400
Yeah.

54:17.680 --> 54:18.300
What is that?

54:18.380 --> 54:18.580
Yeah.

54:18.840 --> 54:21.420
You know what they call the portholes around the top?

54:21.500 --> 54:21.680
Sure.

54:22.520 --> 54:23.980
I do not believe are portholes.

54:23.980 --> 54:24.720
You know what?

54:24.760 --> 54:31.120
I think there's a black ring that goes around the top part of the craft and that's, we call

54:31.120 --> 54:32.300
that the insulator ring.

54:32.960 --> 54:39.980
Um, above that, I have no idea what's in that top section, but that's where these small

54:39.980 --> 54:43.920
square slash rectangular holes are around.

54:44.320 --> 54:51.480
They are assumed to be like some sort of planar array where there is some, something similar

54:51.480 --> 54:53.320
to a computer in the top section.

54:53.320 --> 55:00.360
And those arrays determine whether it's looking at starlight or whatever, uh, it determines

55:00.360 --> 55:02.540
its place in space.

55:04.120 --> 55:06.900
Um, but they, they don't look black.

55:07.000 --> 55:08.320
They look so black.

55:09.700 --> 55:11.760
It's, and it's not just Vantablack.

55:11.860 --> 55:16.560
You know, they almost look like a bottomless pits in there, but I know they're solid.

55:16.560 --> 55:18.240
I mean, Barry told me they're solid.

55:18.980 --> 55:21.760
Um, I guess I don't know.

55:22.040 --> 55:23.160
Barry claimed they're solid.

55:23.340 --> 55:25.720
So to be technical, I don't know for a fact.

55:25.880 --> 55:32.000
I mean, but, um, I still think there's some kind of sensors, but it, it's, that is some

55:32.000 --> 55:33.220
unusual material.

55:33.400 --> 55:39.980
And when you go in there and look at the craft, it's a real ominous, creepy feeling.

55:40.260 --> 55:42.760
And a lot of it is because of the black.

55:43.300 --> 55:45.540
Just, it doesn't, it doesn't look right.

55:45.540 --> 55:49.880
Did anybody else say that going into the craft gave them an ominous feeling?

55:50.380 --> 55:53.900
Yeah, he did say it was, it was definitely unnerving.

55:54.000 --> 55:56.360
I think was his word looking at those.

55:56.780 --> 56:01.960
And, and just being in the craft generally, was that like a kind of ubiquitously known

56:01.960 --> 56:02.980
thing at S4?

56:03.120 --> 56:04.320
Like you walk into that thing?

56:04.580 --> 56:07.400
I didn't hear that from anybody, but it certainly was for me.

56:07.980 --> 56:08.420
Interesting.

56:08.860 --> 56:09.080
Yeah.

56:09.080 --> 56:11.900
Because the first thing you think, boy, that must've been so exciting.

56:11.900 --> 56:18.520
And yeah, from a outsider, it might be, but no, when you're really there, it wasn't exciting.

56:18.700 --> 56:20.140
It was, it was really frightening.

56:20.860 --> 56:24.840
And you walked around the, what looked like the cockpit of this thing?

56:25.840 --> 56:27.700
First of all, you can't just walk in.

56:27.780 --> 56:30.640
It's much smaller and narrower than you think.

56:30.700 --> 56:34.600
You have to crawl in and you really can't stand up until you're almost right in the center.

56:34.600 --> 56:39.540
Um, so it doesn't have really, it's really all unusable space.

56:40.060 --> 56:44.380
Um, even if you're a small creature, there's a lot of unusable space in there.

56:45.020 --> 56:50.800
Um, and you know, because I, everything seemed to have a critical function to it.

56:51.300 --> 56:54.660
Um, I'm sure there was nothing for decoration.

56:54.660 --> 57:00.500
There's a reason to have all that space and the reason the craft is shaped like that.

57:00.940 --> 57:05.420
Um, but there were three things that look like seats.

57:06.300 --> 57:11.660
We call them seats, other humps, large rectangular smooth objects in there.

57:11.740 --> 57:12.740
There were three of those.

57:12.980 --> 57:15.100
Uh, we know those to be the amplifiers.

57:15.100 --> 57:26.060
They work with the, with the reactor that amplifies the gravity wave and it's, you know, channeled to the emitter, which is right under the amplifiers.

57:26.660 --> 57:30.880
Um, again, we just called the seats cause they look like seats.

57:31.060 --> 57:35.340
It would be, I think it would be funny if it turned out that they were not seats at all.

57:35.800 --> 57:39.420
Um, yet another component we just knew nothing about.

57:39.420 --> 57:50.880
Well, Bob always found it to be really weird, uh, that when the wave guide is applied right on top of the reactor, these two guys, they're, they're looking out.

57:50.980 --> 57:53.680
There's a, there's a, one of the archways that become transparent.

57:53.680 --> 57:59.760
So they, he believes that maybe that is where they're looking, but this guy here is staring at a pipe.

57:59.760 --> 58:03.560
Oh, the, the archway becoming transparent is so they can see.

58:03.740 --> 58:03.860
Yeah.

58:04.320 --> 58:06.100
Oh, it's so interesting.

58:06.160 --> 58:07.960
I never like made that connection.

58:08.080 --> 58:08.240
Yeah.

58:08.280 --> 58:09.400
They're looking at it.

58:09.540 --> 58:10.020
Oh.

58:10.200 --> 58:13.220
And there's a screen that appears, the blue screen with a symbol.

58:13.460 --> 58:15.240
With the like Korean like language.

58:15.420 --> 58:15.520
Yeah.

58:15.600 --> 58:21.980
And then I, I've always thought, and I thought maybe they all become transparent.

58:22.060 --> 58:26.080
Maybe the whole arch, like the whole, all the archways can become transparent.

58:26.220 --> 58:28.180
What, why, why would it only be one?

58:28.200 --> 58:29.160
Cause it's so dark in there.

58:29.400 --> 58:29.840
Fascinating.

58:29.840 --> 58:35.740
And you saw a translucent, like almost Korean looking symbols.

58:36.020 --> 58:36.500
Is that right?

58:36.720 --> 58:36.860
Yeah.

58:36.940 --> 58:38.680
I saw the wall become translucent.

58:38.680 --> 58:50.100
And at some point saw some kind of, what I would call symbols, but not on a, in a three-dimensional

58:50.100 --> 58:53.460
way, not on a flat screen or anything like that.

58:53.460 --> 58:55.300
Explain how you saw it.

58:55.300 --> 58:56.780
Cause you were explaining it to me yesterday.

58:56.780 --> 58:56.980
Yeah.

58:56.980 --> 58:58.920
It wasn't like it was a screen.

58:58.920 --> 59:03.760
Um, it was just like, it was a three-dimensional character sitting in there.

59:03.760 --> 59:05.320
Almost like a projection you said.

59:05.940 --> 59:06.280
Yeah.

59:06.520 --> 59:12.680
I, he, he was explaining it to me yesterday because he explained it actually better yesterday

59:12.680 --> 59:14.700
than before I produced it.

59:14.700 --> 59:14.940
Yeah.

59:14.940 --> 59:20.280
And you were saying it felt, it looked almost like a projection on that area.

59:20.280 --> 59:22.720
No, it wasn't a projection or it was on something.

59:22.960 --> 59:25.660
It was just a three-dimensional thing in the air.

59:29.920 --> 59:32.180
Describe the day that you saw this thing fly.

59:32.180 --> 59:40.200
Um, it was already out, um, uh, Barry and I were in the lab and then Dennis came in and

59:40.200 --> 59:41.940
he said, Hey, why don't you guys come?

59:42.280 --> 59:43.960
We're doing a test flight, you know?

59:44.020 --> 59:45.120
So, oh, this is great.

59:45.120 --> 59:48.360
So we go out through the lab door, right into the hangar.

59:48.480 --> 59:52.680
It was already outside, uh, sitting on the ground.

59:53.600 --> 01:00:00.060
And, uh, shortly after we got out there, uh, oh, I did notice there was a radio.

01:00:00.660 --> 01:00:05.460
And I mentioned this in Luigi's movie, a VHF radio and they're in communication.

01:00:05.460 --> 01:00:11.920
So it, it, it made me almost positive that there was somebody in the craft.

01:00:12.260 --> 01:00:12.660
Yep.

01:00:13.220 --> 01:00:13.980
Uh, yeah.

01:00:15.120 --> 01:00:19.960
I don't know how, where they'd be sitting or how they would, why they're even in the

01:00:19.960 --> 01:00:23.100
craft, because it's, like I said, it's so uncomfortable, unusable space.

01:00:23.120 --> 01:00:26.660
They'd have to be hunched up or trying to sit on the edge of one of those seats.

01:00:26.660 --> 01:00:30.880
So, um, that put aside, uh.

01:00:30.960 --> 01:00:32.520
So you think they put a person in there?

01:00:32.680 --> 01:00:35.940
I think so, because they were communicating back and forth.

01:00:36.120 --> 01:00:37.080
Did you hear a voice?

01:00:37.280 --> 01:00:37.460
Yeah.

01:00:37.880 --> 01:00:38.240
Whoa.

01:00:38.400 --> 01:00:38.820
Yeah, yeah.

01:00:39.220 --> 01:00:41.560
So you heard a voice coming from the craft.

01:00:41.740 --> 01:00:42.560
No, from the radio.

01:00:42.920 --> 01:00:44.620
From the radio, from the VHF radio.

01:00:44.620 --> 01:00:44.800
Yeah, yeah.

01:00:44.800 --> 01:00:46.420
But presumably coming from the craft.

01:00:46.500 --> 01:00:46.640
Yeah.

01:00:47.360 --> 01:00:47.760
Wow.

01:00:48.320 --> 01:00:48.560
Yeah.

01:00:48.920 --> 01:00:52.800
So he was monitoring, I mean, they must've had some other instrumentation set up on the

01:00:52.800 --> 01:00:54.740
crafts, because he was monitoring something.

01:00:55.160 --> 01:00:56.300
Do you remember what the voice?

01:00:56.600 --> 01:00:57.020
That was just.

01:00:57.160 --> 01:00:57.740
Not a thing.

01:00:58.040 --> 01:00:58.600
But it was something.

01:00:58.600 --> 01:01:03.640
Because I, I mean, I was more stuck on the fact that, how is a radio wave getting into

01:01:03.640 --> 01:01:04.160
the craft?

01:01:04.240 --> 01:01:05.780
This doesn't even make any sense.

01:01:05.780 --> 01:01:08.480
VHF being very high frequency?

01:01:08.480 --> 01:01:08.840
Yeah.

01:01:09.140 --> 01:01:12.700
I mean, it should be distorted by the gravity wave going around it.

01:01:12.940 --> 01:01:19.320
Anyway, shortly after the craft began to lift off the ground silently, had a little corona

01:01:19.320 --> 01:01:26.280
discharge glow on the bottom and lift it off and drifted up into the sky and kind of moved

01:01:26.280 --> 01:01:26.700
around.

01:01:28.580 --> 01:01:36.840
During that test flight, Dennis motioned for me to come out and, you know, look up at it.

01:01:36.840 --> 01:01:41.100
And then he told me to walk forward and the craft was just sitting there stationary.

01:01:41.740 --> 01:01:46.320
And I walked out underneath it and he motioned for me to look up.

01:01:46.400 --> 01:01:48.260
I looked up and I couldn't see the craft.

01:01:49.340 --> 01:01:51.120
So I thought it flew away.

01:01:52.120 --> 01:01:55.200
And then he said, you know, come back.

01:01:55.660 --> 01:01:58.980
And, you know, I, I walked back and I just walked back.

01:01:59.040 --> 01:02:00.180
It caught my attention.

01:02:00.360 --> 01:02:02.740
I see the edge of the, the craft.

01:02:02.740 --> 01:02:06.560
So if you move, you can see it.

01:02:06.840 --> 01:02:08.960
And if you walk underneath it, you can't.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:11.320
So you can clearly see it's, it's bending the light.

01:02:11.380 --> 01:02:13.040
You can see the sky above the craft.

01:02:13.240 --> 01:02:15.420
So you can see that it's in its little envelope.

01:02:15.740 --> 01:02:22.640
And, um, then it kind of slid over to the left and right and then sat back down.

01:02:23.540 --> 01:02:30.820
Is what you saw, did, did it look like what we talk about when we talk about UFO videos

01:02:30.820 --> 01:02:34.740
and what we, you know, it's just like, look at the, you know, Nimitz, you know, 2004

01:02:34.740 --> 01:02:39.680
FLIR video or, or even some of the, maybe a better example, some of the optical videos,

01:02:39.740 --> 01:02:41.280
which are often grainy and fuzzy.

01:02:41.520 --> 01:02:46.280
And maybe that's due to gravitational lensing or some sort of space time perturbation due

01:02:46.280 --> 01:02:48.140
to these effects that you're talking about.

01:02:48.360 --> 01:02:54.260
But when you're seeing this craft fly, are you thinking this is the UFO stuff that's like

01:02:54.260 --> 01:02:54.920
in the lore?

01:02:55.100 --> 01:02:55.280
Yeah.

01:02:55.480 --> 01:02:56.200
You are.

01:02:56.920 --> 01:02:57.360
Wow.

01:02:57.620 --> 01:02:58.420
Yeah, for sure.

01:02:58.980 --> 01:03:02.960
I'm just because of the, the way that it can move.

01:03:02.960 --> 01:03:10.320
It can just negate, I mean, it's, I really don't know how to describe it.

01:03:10.980 --> 01:03:16.360
Um, I mean, things like inertia really don't matter to it.

01:03:16.740 --> 01:03:16.900
Hmm.

01:03:17.100 --> 01:03:23.740
Um, it just, it gets away with murder when it, when it comes to flying.

01:03:23.740 --> 01:03:31.240
Did you ever think, um, we are being tasked to figure out this reactor, even like, you

01:03:31.240 --> 01:03:34.240
know, the shape of the craft is sort of really confusing to us.

01:03:34.520 --> 01:03:37.320
How the hell do they know how to fly this thing?

01:03:40.540 --> 01:03:40.980
Yeah.

01:03:41.500 --> 01:03:41.940
Yeah.

01:03:42.180 --> 01:03:43.240
That goes through your head.

01:03:43.240 --> 01:03:48.800
Like you're like, yeah, well, I mean, yeah, like I said, you know, clearly they've, they've

01:03:48.800 --> 01:03:51.620
had a lot of time with this craft already.

01:03:51.840 --> 01:03:54.800
It could have been decades for all I know.

01:03:54.900 --> 01:03:56.300
So they're familiar with it.

01:03:56.400 --> 01:04:02.300
So, I mean, they, they knew the emitters have to be rotated, you know, to couple to the

01:04:02.300 --> 01:04:02.780
reactor.

01:04:02.780 --> 01:04:05.220
I mean, they knew how to fly it.

01:04:05.580 --> 01:04:11.340
Um, so that these guys were somewhat proficient with it, but it, so it would be your kind

01:04:11.340 --> 01:04:18.580
of base case assumption that now we have functional, what you might call alien reproduction

01:04:18.580 --> 01:04:21.920
vehicles or UFOs that humans can fly.

01:04:21.920 --> 01:04:29.740
If in 1987, 88, you had stuff that was, you know, we could at least test and you could go

01:04:29.740 --> 01:04:33.520
under them and stuff, then you would think that now we're probably, we've probably made

01:04:33.520 --> 01:04:36.580
much more progress, I assume, or what, what, what do you think?

01:04:37.300 --> 01:04:38.600
I do not think so.

01:04:38.680 --> 01:04:38.840
No.

01:04:39.100 --> 01:04:39.880
You don't think so.

01:04:40.080 --> 01:04:40.260
No.

01:04:40.660 --> 01:04:45.440
So you think we're, we can test these things and use them in a rudimentary ways, but we

01:04:45.440 --> 01:04:47.500
don't understand how they work.

01:04:47.500 --> 01:04:54.880
No, it's like the, you know, analogy I, I gave, you know, you can go back to the 1800s

01:04:54.880 --> 01:04:56.920
and drop off a motorcycle.

01:04:57.240 --> 01:04:57.520
Yep.

01:04:57.700 --> 01:04:58.720
With the keys in it.

01:04:58.720 --> 01:05:04.480
And, you know, you can look at it and go, wow, that's never seen anything like that before

01:05:04.480 --> 01:05:09.340
and look at the plastic fenders on it and wow, that's unusual material.

01:05:09.340 --> 01:05:11.040
And, you know, there's the key.

01:05:11.140 --> 01:05:14.180
And eventually if you tinker with it long enough, someone's going to turn the key and

01:05:14.180 --> 01:05:14.940
it's going to start.

01:05:15.640 --> 01:05:16.040
Yep.

01:05:16.040 --> 01:05:19.420
And they're going to go, okay, we turn it off and go, all right, that's on and off.

01:05:19.520 --> 01:05:25.080
And, you know, eventually just given time and human, human ingenuity, they're going to

01:05:25.080 --> 01:05:29.360
get it throttles here and they'll become proficient at driving it.

01:05:29.700 --> 01:05:29.980
Yeah.

01:05:30.620 --> 01:05:32.820
But when it runs out of fuel, we're done.

01:05:33.240 --> 01:05:36.700
And when it comes right down to it, they can't even make that plastic fender.

01:05:36.980 --> 01:05:37.340
Right.

01:05:37.340 --> 01:05:39.120
So, yeah.

01:05:39.240 --> 01:05:42.560
So, you can become proficient at using it.

01:05:42.960 --> 01:05:44.720
And I think that's where we are.

01:05:44.880 --> 01:05:46.480
We had some knowledge of that.

01:05:46.620 --> 01:05:53.300
But I think if we had developed that technology, we would have absolutely already seen it.

01:05:53.960 --> 01:05:58.880
We wouldn't be wasting one minute building a conventional fighter or other.

01:05:59.240 --> 01:05:59.680
Why?

01:06:00.040 --> 01:06:01.020
Why would you?

01:06:01.400 --> 01:06:02.700
And they say, oh, well, it's secret.

01:06:02.860 --> 01:06:03.000
Yep.

01:06:03.160 --> 01:06:08.420
So, jet engines were secret when we first came out with them and we built a whole fleet.

01:06:08.640 --> 01:06:14.580
You know, we'd absolutely divert every resource we had to duplicating these things.

