That's like a Ford making an engine and it goes in, you know, a bunch of different models.

01:34:45.980 --> 01:34:53.200
How can all these crafts have the same, you know, the same power system or propulsion system

01:34:53.200 --> 01:34:53.500
in them?

01:34:53.500 --> 01:34:59.040
Um, anyway, I don't want to go off on a tangent, but he had a reactor.

01:34:59.220 --> 01:35:05.180
So it was probably from some, one of the other crafts and why they did this is beyond

01:35:05.180 --> 01:35:05.580
me.

01:35:05.800 --> 01:35:13.060
They took it out to the nuclear test site and they physically cut into it while it was

01:35:13.060 --> 01:35:15.440
running under load and it exploded.

01:35:15.940 --> 01:35:19.800
And all, I think there were three guys there, maybe more.

01:35:19.920 --> 01:35:20.760
They were all killed.

01:35:23.500 --> 01:35:26.920
So, number one, why would you do that?

01:35:27.940 --> 01:35:34.600
Number, number two, it makes me think either they were extremely desperate and want to just,

01:35:34.720 --> 01:35:40.480
well, find out what's in there and, you know, and, uh, why would you even do it while it was

01:35:40.480 --> 01:35:41.020
operating?

01:35:41.020 --> 01:35:46.500
They were extremely confident or extremely confident that they knew what was going on

01:35:46.500 --> 01:35:48.440
in the reactor, where they could safely cut it.

01:35:48.620 --> 01:35:50.900
And they had a reason to get in there.

01:35:51.700 --> 01:35:57.840
Um, but apparently that information never made it back, whatever they gleaned from it,

01:35:57.840 --> 01:36:02.880
or even their suspicions at the beginning, because Barry and I were kind of starting from the

01:36:02.880 --> 01:36:03.900
beginning on the reactor.

01:36:04.660 --> 01:36:09.900
Uh, so everything they had done previously was lost.

01:36:12.140 --> 01:36:12.580
Anyway.

01:36:12.980 --> 01:36:17.660
You ever learn the guy's name or any details about, do you, does Barry have a last name or?

01:36:18.140 --> 01:36:18.420
Yeah.

01:36:18.520 --> 01:36:25.940
Barry, uh, Castillo, it's spelled Castillo, but Castile, I don't know how it's pronounced.

01:36:26.120 --> 01:36:26.280
Yeah.

01:36:26.400 --> 01:36:28.300
Have you ever tracked him down after?

01:36:28.860 --> 01:36:34.820
I think briefly decades ago, we made a real, cause there was another guy that would come

01:36:34.820 --> 01:36:36.580
in and out once in a while named Renee.

01:36:36.920 --> 01:36:37.200
Okay.

01:36:37.500 --> 01:36:43.540
Don't remember his last name, but I mean, at, at some point I really put a lot of effort

01:36:43.540 --> 01:36:46.200
into trying to find Dennis Mariani and Barry.

01:36:46.200 --> 01:36:49.460
And, uh, I think some people did track down Dennis.

01:36:49.720 --> 01:36:51.960
I think he died not too long ago.

01:36:52.160 --> 01:36:52.340
Okay.

01:36:52.340 --> 01:36:58.220
Um, I don't know about Barry, but, uh, I, I never was never able to find it.

01:36:58.220 --> 01:37:02.100
Cause I mean, back in the time I was looking for him, there was no internet, you know, so

01:37:02.100 --> 01:37:07.060
you had to go through public records and stuff and, uh, it was much more difficult than it

01:37:07.060 --> 01:37:07.500
is now.

01:37:07.680 --> 01:37:07.960
Yeah.

01:37:08.200 --> 01:37:14.160
And I, I know of one instance in which the name Dennis Mariani was corroborated by somebody

01:37:14.160 --> 01:37:16.860
at, you know, uh, Nevada test site.

01:37:16.900 --> 01:37:21.480
And so, um, uh, you know, I won't, I won't go further than that, but, uh,

01:37:21.480 --> 01:37:23.100
because it's not right.

01:37:23.140 --> 01:37:29.240
It's not my thing to tell, but you're, you're giving names and, you know, I think some of

01:37:29.240 --> 01:37:32.360
these people could still be alive, which is pretty remarkable to you.

01:37:32.640 --> 01:37:35.780
Like maybe we could track some of them down and they could back you up.

01:37:35.820 --> 01:37:37.600
I wonder, I mean, they have to know.

01:37:37.600 --> 01:37:41.920
I'm kind of wondering why nobody else came out, you know?

01:37:42.240 --> 01:37:42.540
Yeah.

01:37:42.540 --> 01:37:51.220
Um, I mean, although Barry wouldn't talk about it much, you know, um, there are times I kind

01:37:51.220 --> 01:37:55.680
of mentioned, you know, holy cow, can you believe this is being kept secret?

01:37:55.820 --> 01:37:57.780
And he goes, I, it sucks.

01:37:57.900 --> 01:37:58.320
I know.

01:37:58.580 --> 01:37:58.680
Yeah.

01:37:58.720 --> 01:38:04.600
So he didn't think it was, you know, he wasn't with the program as far as keeping this from,

01:38:04.640 --> 01:38:06.140
you know, the entire world.

01:38:06.300 --> 01:38:07.340
What was his background?

01:38:07.740 --> 01:38:08.420
No idea.

01:38:08.700 --> 01:38:09.000
Okay.

01:38:09.600 --> 01:38:10.200
No idea.

01:38:10.200 --> 01:38:14.540
Um, but there was kind of a collegial goodwill between you and him.

01:38:14.540 --> 01:38:14.740
Yeah.

01:38:15.000 --> 01:38:15.260
Yeah.

01:38:15.700 --> 01:38:15.940
Yeah.

01:38:16.100 --> 01:38:21.900
And he'd goof around sometimes, which was nice because everything else was just so rigid

01:38:21.900 --> 01:38:22.660
and military.

01:38:22.980 --> 01:38:29.240
So, you know, I'm sure the story where he threw the golf ball at the reactor and, you know,

01:38:29.280 --> 01:38:32.280
sometimes we'd start just start talking about stupid stuff.

01:38:32.360 --> 01:38:38.960
So it was, it's good to see a normal person, you know, that just acted like, you know, a human

01:38:38.960 --> 01:38:40.180
instead of a robot.

01:38:40.880 --> 01:38:42.840
What happened when he threw the golf ball at the reactor?

01:38:43.220 --> 01:38:48.660
He was showing me the field on it and he said, check this out and took a golf ball and,

01:38:48.660 --> 01:38:50.580
you know, intending to hit the reactor.

01:38:50.580 --> 01:38:57.340
And instead it bounced off the field and then hit a ceiling tile, which dislodged it and made

01:38:57.340 --> 01:38:59.560
all the little particles, you know, come down.

01:38:59.560 --> 01:39:02.700
And we knew Dennis was going to be coming back in two minutes.

01:39:02.880 --> 01:39:05.440
So it was, you know, red alert.

01:39:05.580 --> 01:39:10.100
We had to, you know, grab the stools and go up and re-ascend and clean it up and everything.

01:39:10.760 --> 01:39:13.920
And, you know, shortly after that, Dennis walks in and says, you know, what's going on?

01:39:14.040 --> 01:39:14.960
Nothing, nothing.

01:39:15.500 --> 01:39:19.220
You know, we're working like we should be.

01:39:19.220 --> 01:39:24.180
I mean, this is a remarkable detail around the reactor.

01:39:24.340 --> 01:39:28.180
You have this sort of force field like thing, this like repelling force.

01:39:28.340 --> 01:39:28.460
Yeah.

01:39:28.920 --> 01:39:29.120
Yeah.

01:39:29.420 --> 01:39:34.480
Once the, uh, a hemisphere on top of a plate, you know, about the size of a basketball,

01:39:34.720 --> 01:39:41.240
maybe a little bigger on top of a 15 inch square plate, um, the hemisphere is removable.

01:39:41.620 --> 01:39:47.940
Once the hemisphere is put back on, um, if the emitter is in the right position,

01:39:47.940 --> 01:39:53.560
the reactor will turn on immediately and it'll produce a gravitational field around it and

01:39:53.560 --> 01:39:59.360
you can push on it and you, you can't, you can't touch the reactor from that point.

01:39:59.520 --> 01:40:05.440
I mean, it, and it, it's somewhat elastic, you know, like if you have two light poles

01:40:05.440 --> 01:40:09.900
of a magnet pushing them together, you get that it's the exact same field, but without

01:40:09.900 --> 01:40:11.140
metal, it's just your hands.

01:40:11.760 --> 01:40:17.740
But as I said before, what, what's really interesting is, you know, you can move the

01:40:17.740 --> 01:40:25.660
reactor on the table and once you turn it on and you're pushing on the field, the reactor

01:40:25.660 --> 01:40:26.900
doesn't slide.

01:40:27.780 --> 01:40:31.340
So it's not transferring the force to the reactor.

01:40:32.020 --> 01:40:33.920
It's pushing your hand away.

01:40:34.760 --> 01:40:39.060
But so that's, it's, it's really interesting to me.

01:40:39.660 --> 01:40:41.040
How did the reactor work?

01:40:41.980 --> 01:40:43.400
This is all guess.

01:40:43.620 --> 01:40:45.140
This is just all guesswork.

01:40:45.320 --> 01:40:45.540
Yes.

01:40:45.540 --> 01:40:52.280
Um, it has a super heavy element in it, which appeared to be 115 on the periodic chart.

01:40:52.920 --> 01:41:00.300
Uh, there's a little tower in it and from x-rays, we could see that there's a loop around

01:41:00.300 --> 01:41:01.200
the base plate.

01:41:01.460 --> 01:41:06.900
So it was theorized, apparently Barry with his other lab partner.

01:41:06.900 --> 01:41:16.540
They thought that was a, uh, cyclotron, an accelerator, and that the tube that came up the side was an

01:41:16.540 --> 01:41:17.640
off-ramp, essentially.

01:41:17.960 --> 01:41:25.260
And that particle or whatever was being accelerated interacts with the 115 and somehow that produces

01:41:25.260 --> 01:41:26.720
the gravitational field.

01:41:26.720 --> 01:41:31.640
How did it feel on your hand?

01:41:32.360 --> 01:41:35.360
It, it, it felt exactly like pushing magnets together.

01:41:35.700 --> 01:41:36.180
Okay.

01:41:36.360 --> 01:41:37.840
It was just elastic.

01:41:38.200 --> 01:41:40.580
I mean, it was compressible to some degree.

01:41:40.780 --> 01:41:45.360
And then when it got close to it, you're nothing is getting past that.

01:41:46.020 --> 01:41:49.380
With magnets, you have to have like pulls for them to repel.

01:41:49.640 --> 01:41:49.880
Yeah.

01:41:49.880 --> 01:41:56.860
And in this case, you're not, you know, it's just a matter repelling matter without polarity.

01:41:57.300 --> 01:42:00.960
Does it feel like a, what does it feel like?

01:42:01.020 --> 01:42:03.080
Does it, is there a texture to it or?

01:42:03.240 --> 01:42:08.580
No, it's just, it's just elastic, but it, it, it becomes, it's not linear.

01:42:08.900 --> 01:42:14.100
But does it feel like it's logarithmic, you know, it's, it's easy to push and then it becomes

01:42:14.100 --> 01:42:14.620
impossible.

01:42:15.860 --> 01:42:17.860
There's no way you're getting past the next three inches.

01:42:17.860 --> 01:42:21.340
You could probably sit a car on top of it and nothing would change.

01:42:21.840 --> 01:42:28.240
Does it feel like saran wrap or does it feel like, like, what, what does it feel like when

01:42:28.240 --> 01:42:28.920
you're in it?

01:42:29.000 --> 01:42:30.080
Does it feel like.

01:42:31.140 --> 01:42:32.340
No, it just feels.

01:42:33.420 --> 01:42:35.840
It's literally like air, like.

01:42:35.960 --> 01:42:36.180
Yeah.

01:42:36.180 --> 01:42:37.440
I see what you're saying.

01:42:37.540 --> 01:42:38.040
You know what I mean?

01:42:38.060 --> 01:42:38.700
I describe that.

01:42:38.820 --> 01:42:39.120
Yeah.

01:42:39.880 --> 01:42:41.060
Like, is there a.

01:42:41.180 --> 01:42:41.840
No, it just.

01:42:42.140 --> 01:42:43.300
Coolness, a heat.

01:42:43.600 --> 01:42:43.860
No.

01:42:44.620 --> 01:42:44.940
No.

01:42:45.140 --> 01:42:47.220
It's just like space time itself.

01:42:48.620 --> 01:42:49.060
Yeah.

01:42:49.180 --> 01:42:50.000
It's just.

01:42:51.520 --> 01:42:53.040
I don't know how to describe it.

01:42:53.120 --> 01:42:53.280
Sure.

01:42:53.380 --> 01:42:53.540
Sure.

01:42:53.700 --> 01:42:53.720
Yeah.

01:42:53.720 --> 01:42:55.120
But it's, it's just there.

01:43:01.180 --> 01:43:04.800
I mean, at this point, I don't, I don't even think it's gravity.

01:43:05.340 --> 01:43:05.980
What do you think?

01:43:05.980 --> 01:43:08.480
I think this is an, another completely unique force.

01:43:09.080 --> 01:43:11.360
It doesn't behave enough like gravity.

01:43:11.940 --> 01:43:14.740
And explain why it's so different.

01:43:15.160 --> 01:43:21.580
Like, I mean, because at least my thoughts at this point are, I think gravity is just

01:43:21.580 --> 01:43:24.340
a property of matter and it's only an attractive force.

01:43:24.340 --> 01:43:27.040
I'm not sure you can have anti-gravity.

01:43:27.820 --> 01:43:34.500
Um, like if it was gravity, you know, at one point, Barry showed me, he had one of the

01:43:34.500 --> 01:43:36.240
emitters, it working.

01:43:36.440 --> 01:43:42.960
He put a lit little kitchen candle right at the focal point and he powered up the, the

01:43:42.960 --> 01:43:46.160
reactor and the flame stopped flickering.

01:43:46.420 --> 01:43:49.440
It stood there frozen in space and time.

01:43:49.440 --> 01:43:54.300
And, but I could see the light from the candle, the flame was still visible.

01:43:55.720 --> 01:44:00.640
Also, he removed the candle and then rotated the emitter.

01:44:01.040 --> 01:44:04.820
I don't know if it was another direction or more of the same way, but it made a little

01:44:04.820 --> 01:44:09.840
black ball in the air where no light was escaping, looking like a little black hole.

01:44:10.480 --> 01:44:15.260
But no, you could just tell there was no light at the focal point right in the air.

01:44:15.480 --> 01:44:17.140
It was just a dark area.

01:44:17.140 --> 01:44:22.960
So there it's affecting light, but it wasn't in the candle test before that.

01:44:23.280 --> 01:44:28.260
So it, it, it's a really unusual, unusual thing.

01:44:31.560 --> 01:44:37.440
When Bob mentioned this anomalous force coming from the craft's emitter, I immediately racked

01:44:37.440 --> 01:44:42.640
my brain for anyone in conventional aerospace circles who talks about something similar.

01:44:42.640 --> 01:44:48.180
And then I realized I just interviewed the lead electrostatic scientist at NASA, Dr.

01:44:48.280 --> 01:44:51.120
Charles Buehler, who talks about something very similar.

01:44:51.460 --> 01:44:51.580
Okay.

01:44:51.620 --> 01:44:53.260
Where the heck is this energy coming from?

01:44:53.520 --> 01:44:59.460
Because if I was to stick this in space, it would accelerate with the power off.

01:44:59.960 --> 01:45:00.600
That's a problem.

01:45:00.600 --> 01:45:09.180
You see, there's a long lineage of people studying gravity control or anti-gravity in the United

01:45:09.180 --> 01:45:09.760
States.

01:45:09.760 --> 01:45:16.440
Perhaps my favorite example is mid-century inventor Thomas Townsend Brown, who discovered that

01:45:16.440 --> 01:45:21.960
when you apply a high voltage to certain asymmetric capacitors, they produce thrust.

01:45:21.960 --> 01:45:22.900
That's right.

01:45:23.120 --> 01:45:30.520
Propulsion with no fuel, no exhaust, no propellant, just electricity as the input, converted directly

01:45:30.520 --> 01:45:31.320
into motion.

01:45:31.500 --> 01:45:36.680
A new model for space propulsion that could eliminate crude chemical combustion rockets

01:45:36.680 --> 01:45:37.420
forever.

01:45:38.120 --> 01:45:41.640
Now you might think that's insane and defies Newton's laws.

01:45:41.860 --> 01:45:46.380
And I'll spare you all of the corroborating research that I've dug up showing that Brown

01:45:46.380 --> 01:45:49.080
made real breakthroughs in the world of anti-gravity.

01:45:49.080 --> 01:45:56.440
Dr. Charles Buehler at NASA has taken Brown's experiments to the next level, with modern

01:45:56.440 --> 01:46:07.120
instruments, more rigorous controls, and decades of electrostatics expertise from his work at

01:46:07.120 --> 01:46:08.920
Kennedy Space Center behind him.

01:46:09.240 --> 01:46:14.640
He's done over 2,000 of these experiments and controlled for just about every variable

01:46:14.640 --> 01:46:15.660
you can think of.

01:46:15.660 --> 01:46:21.260
And he's also getting millinewtons of thrust, basically real propulsion with electricity as

01:46:21.260 --> 01:46:22.320
the sole input.

01:46:22.700 --> 01:46:25.940
And you can't really argue with his authority to make these claims.

01:46:26.180 --> 01:46:29.200
The man literally runs electrostatics at NASA.

01:46:29.720 --> 01:46:33.560
He's the incoming president of the American Electrostatic Society.

01:46:34.160 --> 01:46:39.860
And he's contributed two fundamental principles to the field of electrostatics that are now

01:46:39.860 --> 01:46:40.980
widely accepted.

01:46:40.980 --> 01:46:45.740
So this is kind of an interesting moment in history, because we have a man who reverse

01:46:45.740 --> 01:46:51.040
engineered UFOs, and then we have a NASA lead electrostatic scientist.

01:46:51.400 --> 01:46:55.040
So I thought I'd just leave it to you guys to kind of nerd out.

01:46:55.280 --> 01:46:56.860
Yeah, well, first of all, hi, Charles.

01:46:58.020 --> 01:46:58.520
Hi, Bob.

01:46:58.560 --> 01:47:00.260
This is a very exciting moment for me.

01:47:00.340 --> 01:47:01.160
I'm a big fan.

01:47:01.800 --> 01:47:05.480
Now, the thing about Bob Lazar is he kind of exists on an island.

01:47:05.480 --> 01:47:10.260
We've never seen him interact with other highly credentialed engineers in aerospace.

01:47:11.060 --> 01:47:15.560
And what I've learned after spending time with him is he's actually pretty skeptical when

01:47:15.560 --> 01:47:17.540
it comes to other scientific anomalies.

01:47:17.780 --> 01:47:22.940
Man, I'm real interested to hear, you know, your physical experiment setup.

01:47:23.240 --> 01:47:26.460
Is it a hybrid of your idea and T.T.

01:47:26.860 --> 01:47:29.940
Brown's, or are you just duplicating one of his experiments?

01:47:29.940 --> 01:47:34.540
I mean, what, can you explain to me what it looks like?

01:47:34.620 --> 01:47:36.140
What's your test setup look like?

01:47:36.820 --> 01:47:38.500
Gosh, there's 2,000 variations.

01:47:38.900 --> 01:47:40.120
I'll try to do my best.

01:47:41.700 --> 01:47:49.460
I mean, how is this, I'm sure you've seen the lifter ion motors and stuff along those

01:47:49.460 --> 01:47:49.700
lines.

01:47:49.920 --> 01:47:52.500
How is it different from those?

01:47:52.880 --> 01:47:53.500
A few ways.

01:47:53.500 --> 01:48:00.580
The ion thrusters obviously use ions in the air to give them momentum oscillation.

01:48:00.840 --> 01:48:06.720
What's interesting about this force, even though it's sort of the same geometry can be

01:48:06.720 --> 01:48:10.640
used, but in high vacuum, you'll get the thrust.

01:48:10.860 --> 01:48:14.240
But it's always in the opposite direction of the ion thrusters, which is really cool.

01:48:14.400 --> 01:48:17.200
Because what happens is you have a sharp electrode in the ground plane.

01:48:17.660 --> 01:48:20.200
However you do that, you can come up with a million ways to do that.

01:48:20.200 --> 01:48:24.120
So in air, when you do that, you'll break down the gases, either in the corona or some

01:48:24.120 --> 01:48:24.880
fold like that.

01:48:25.740 --> 01:48:32.760
In vacuum, we can actually see these forces arise, but they're always in the opposite direction

01:48:32.760 --> 01:48:34.340
of the ion wind, which is really interesting.

01:48:35.360 --> 01:48:36.020
That is very interesting.

01:48:36.040 --> 01:48:37.620
It's the same direction as the rocket exhaust.

01:48:37.760 --> 01:48:38.540
You never think of that.

01:48:38.800 --> 01:48:40.420
So it really messes with you.

01:48:40.800 --> 01:48:42.180
So that's what's interesting about it.

01:48:42.200 --> 01:48:43.160
That's one main difference.

01:48:43.600 --> 01:48:43.620
Wow.

01:48:44.160 --> 01:48:44.280
Yeah.

01:48:44.440 --> 01:48:45.940
Well, that's really interesting.

01:48:45.940 --> 01:48:52.020
I mean, the fact that it's in the opposite direction of where an ion thruster would be.

01:48:52.160 --> 01:48:56.960
And you've done it in a hard or reasonably hard vacuum, and you're getting measurable thrust?

01:48:58.020 --> 01:48:58.900
Oh, we have.

01:48:58.960 --> 01:49:00.340
We've been doing that since 2020.

01:49:00.920 --> 01:49:06.600
So the last six years, we test almost every day, probably every other day, different configurations

01:49:06.600 --> 01:49:10.740
or zero in on a configuration, test another concept.

01:49:10.740 --> 01:49:14.020
And that is an ongoing iterative process.

01:49:14.800 --> 01:49:17.880
So yes, we have tested a high vacuum, 10 to the minus six or better.

01:49:18.020 --> 01:49:21.020
The champion can get up to 10 to the minus seven, but enough to prove to us that there's

01:49:21.020 --> 01:49:21.680
no ion wind.

01:49:22.580 --> 01:49:25.160
What kind of thrust in newtons or grams are you getting?

01:49:25.440 --> 01:49:30.480
Well, we're still playing around in the hundreds of microneutons or millineuton ranges.

01:49:31.040 --> 01:49:35.000
So I think the highest we've gotten is probably up to the 50 millineuton mark.

01:49:35.000 --> 01:49:38.100
But that's when we stack these together.

01:49:38.700 --> 01:49:42.080
We don't learn a lot from them when we do that, other than we can make more thrust,

01:49:42.260 --> 01:49:42.800
which is important.

01:49:43.580 --> 01:49:48.440
But we like to understand the thrust density, if you will, of each thruster.

01:49:48.560 --> 01:49:54.280
So we're trying to optimize each type, optimize each parameter space that we have access to

